VALUES
(40, 14, 11, 1, 49, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Wrath and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of violent consequences stemming from anger and wrath. In Matthew, the brutal act of beheading reflects the fierce anger described in Genesis, illustrating the destructive outcomes of unchecked emotions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 11, 20, 27, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Wrath and Envy', 'This connection highlights the destructive nature of emotions. In Matthew, the act of bringing John''s head reflects the cruelty of envy and anger, while Proverbs explicitly states that wrath is cruel and questions who can withstand envy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 11, 20, 29, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Bloodthirsty and Justice', 'This connection highlights the theme of violence against the just. In Matthew, the act of bringing the head signifies a bloodthirsty act, while Proverbs contrasts this with the just seeking righteousness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 11, 24, 22, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Innocent Blood', 'This connection highlights the theme of shedding innocent blood. In Matthew, the beheading of John the Baptist represents violence against the innocent, while Jeremiah condemns the shedding of innocent blood as part of oppression and violence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 11, 26, 16, 3, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Birth and Identity', 'This connection highlights themes of identity and origin. Both passages discuss the beginnings of a person or entity, with Matthew referencing the presentation of a head, symbolizing a definitive end, while Ezekiel reflects on the uncut navel, indicating a neglected beginning.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 11, 26, 19, 2, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Nourishment and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the act of bringing forth something significant. In Matthew, the head is brought to the mother, while in Ezekiel, the lioness brings up her whelp, highlighting themes of nurturing and the consequences of that nurturing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 12, 44, 8, 2, 2, 'buried', 'Burial and Lamentation Practices', 'Both passages emphasize the act of burial and the mourning that follows. In Matthew, the disciples bury John the Baptist, while in Acts, devout men carry Stephen to his burial and lament over him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 12, 40, 27, 58, 61, 'took up the body, and buried it', 'Burial of the Body', 'This connection highlights the act of taking and burying a body in both passages. In Matthew 14:12, the disciples bury John the Baptist, while in Matthew 27:58-61, Joseph of Arimathea takes and buries Jesus, emphasizing the theme of burial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 13, 42, 9, 10, 17, 'desert place', 'Desert Place and Feeding Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus departing to a ''desert place'' where he interacts with a large crowd. They highlight the miraculous feeding of the multitude, showcasing Jesus'' compassion and ability to provide. This connection illustrates a shared theme of Jesus'' ministry in remote areas.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 13, 40, 14, 1, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus and John', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' identity. In Matthew 14:1-2, Herod associates Jesus with John the Baptist, while Matthew 14:13 shows the people''s response to Jesus'' fame.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 13, 40, 12, 15, 15, NULL, 'Jesus'' Withdrawal and Following Crowds', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' withdrawal and the subsequent following of great multitudes. This connection highlights the pattern of Jesus seeking solitude while still attracting large crowds.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 13, 41, 6, 30, 44, 'desert place', 'Desert Place Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the ''desert place'' where Jesus and his disciples sought solitude. The movement of the people following Jesus highlights their desire to be near him, leading to the miraculous feeding of the 5,000.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 13, 43, 6, 1, 15, 'the people had heard thereof, they followed him', 'Miracle of Feeding the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of a large crowd following Jesus, highlighting his compassion and miraculous provision of food. The connection is evident in the shared theme of Jesus responding to the needs of the people in a desolate place.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 58, 4, 15, 15, 'moved with compassion toward them', 'Compassion and Infirmities Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of compassion in both passages. In Matthew, Jesus is moved with compassion and heals the sick, while Hebrews emphasizes that the high priest is touched with the feeling of our infirmities.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 40, 9, 36, 36, 'moved with compassion', 'Compassion for the Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' compassion for the crowds. In each instance, he responds to their needs, highlighting his role as a healer and shepherd.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 43, 11, 33, 35, 'moved with compassion', 'Compassion and Weeping of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' emotional response to suffering. In Matthew, he is ''moved with compassion'' for the sick, while in John, he is ''troubled'' and ''wept'' for those mourning. This connection highlights Jesus'' deep empathy in the face of human pain.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 58, 2, 17, 17, 'moved with compassion toward them', 'Compassion and Merciful Priesthood', 'This connection highlights the theme of compassion in both passages. In Matthew, Jesus is moved with compassion to heal, while Hebrews describes Him as a merciful high priest, emphasizing His role in caring for humanity.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 40, 15, 32, 39, 'moved with compassion toward them', 'Compassion for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' compassion for the multitude, first in healing their sick and then in providing food for them. This connection highlights His concern for their physical and spiritual needs.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 41, 6, 34, 34, 'moved with compassion toward them', 'Compassion for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' compassion for the crowds. They highlight his response to their needs, with healing in Matthew and teaching in Mark.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 14, 41, 9, 22, 22, NULL, 'Compassion in Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of compassion in the context of healing. In Matthew, Jesus is moved with compassion to heal the sick, while in Mark, the plea for help is rooted in a request for compassion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 15, 40, 15, 23, 23, NULL, 'Disciples'' Concern for Crowds', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' concern for the needs of the people. In Matthew 14:15, they suggest sending the multitude away for food, while in Matthew 15:23, they ask Jesus to send away a woman seeking help, indicating a recurring theme of managing the crowd''s needs.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 15, 41, 6, 35, 36, 'this is a desert place', 'Disciples'' Concern for Food', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' concern for the crowd''s lack of food in a desert place. They express the need to send the multitude away to buy victuals or bread, highlighting a shared situation of scarcity.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 15, 41, 8, 3, 3, 'send the multitude away', 'Connection of Compassion for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the concern for the crowd''s needs. In Matthew, the disciples suggest sending the multitude away for food, while in Mark, Jesus expresses worry that they will faint on their way home. This connection highlights the theme of caring for those who are in need.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 15, 42, 9, 12, 12, 'send the multitude away', 'Disciples'' Concern for the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' request to send the crowd away due to the desert location and lack of provisions. This connection highlights a shared concern for the needs of the people in a desolate area.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 16, 12, 4, 42, 44, 'give ye them to eat', 'Provision for the Hungry', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous provision of food for a multitude. In each case, a small amount of food is multiplied to satisfy the needs of many, demonstrating God''s ability to provide abundantly.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 16, 47, 8, 2, 3, 'give ye them to eat', 'Liberality in Giving', 'This connection highlights the theme of generosity in both passages. In Matthew, Jesus encourages the disciples to provide for the needs of others, while in 2 Corinthians, the Macedonian churches demonstrate their willingness to give beyond their means despite their poverty.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 16, 20, 11, 24, 24, 'give ye them to eat', 'Generosity and Provision', 'This connection highlights the theme of generosity leading to abundance. Both passages emphasize the idea that giving, rather than withholding, results in greater provision.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 16, 21, 11, 2, 2, 'give ye them to eat', 'Provision and Generosity Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of providing for others in need. Both passages emphasize the importance of giving and sharing resources, as seen in Jesus'' directive to feed the people and the advice to distribute portions wisely.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 16, 43, 13, 29, 29, 'give ye them to eat', 'Provision and Responsibility', 'This connection highlights the theme of providing for needs. In Matthew, Jesus emphasizes giving food to the people, while in John, the disciples consider purchasing items for the feast, reflecting a concern for provision.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 14, 16, 18, 31, 16, 17, 'give ye them to eat', 'Compassion for the Needy', 'This connection highlights the theme of providing for those in need. Both passages emphasize the importance of not withholding food from the poor and ensuring that everyone is fed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
